and was a member

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:09.430
of President Obama's cabinet.

00:01:09.430 --> 00:01:11.900
Before joining
the US government,

00:01:11.900 --> 00:01:15.700
she was the founding executive
of the Carr Center for Human

00:01:15.700 --> 00:01:18.610
Rights Policy, again
at the Kennedy School,

00:01:18.610 --> 00:01:21.100
and among her many
writings, many of you

00:01:21.100 --> 00:01:24.790
will recognize her famous
Pulitzer Prize winning

00:01:24.790 --> 00:01:27.760
book, A Problem
From Hell, America

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:29.170
and the Age of Genocide.

00:01:29.170 --> 00:01:32.620
We're very honored to have
her and our other panelists

00:01:32.620 --> 00:01:33.317
with us.

00:01:33.317 --> 00:01:34.150
Thank you very much.

00:01:34.150 --> 00:01:35.578
- Thank you.

00:01:40.340 --> 00:01:41.159
Hi, everybody.

00:01:41.159 --> 00:01:42.950
I was supposed to have
the easiest job here

00:01:42.950 --> 00:01:46.130
today, which was just to
introduce our panelists

00:01:46.130 --> 00:01:48.740
and moderate the discussion.

00:01:48.740 --> 00:01:52.085
But because, as you'll hear, the
emphasis of the other panelists

00:01:52.085 --> 00:01:54.040
is on other parts
of the world, I've

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:56.570
been asked, at the last minute--

00:01:56.570 --> 00:02:00.530
given the unfortunate
absence of the person

00:02:00.530 --> 00:02:03.050
who was to be our
third panelist,

00:02:03.050 --> 00:02:06.920
who's a tremendous immigration
rights activist and organizer

00:02:06.920 --> 00:02:08.097
here in this country--

00:02:08.097 --> 00:02:10.430
I've been asked to speak a
little bit at the last minute

00:02:10.430 --> 00:02:14.630
to some of the immigration
and citizenship issues

00:02:14.630 --> 00:02:16.419
as they relate to
the United States.

00:02:16.419 --> 00:02:17.960
So I'm going to do
that very briefly,

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:21.200
but before I do that, it
gives me great pleasure

00:02:21.200 --> 00:02:25.490
to give you a preview of the
more substantive presentations

00:02:25.490 --> 00:02:29.640
that we'll be getting from
two extraordinary panelists.

00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:32.790
Sarah Leah Whitson is
the Executive Director,

00:02:32.790 --> 00:02:35.330
as you know from your program,
of Human Rights Watch, Middle

00:02:35.330 --> 00:02:38.030
East and North
Africa's Division,

00:02:38.030 --> 00:02:40.190
and she is going to
speak about the changing

00:02:40.190 --> 00:02:44.090
landscape for women's
rights in the Middle East.

00:02:44.090 --> 00:02:47.000
She will focus, I
think, very specifically

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:50.210
on a country that's been
a lot in the news of late,

00:02:50.210 --> 00:02:53.700
in terms of the steps that
it has taken regarding women.

00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:56.150
I will leave that
country nameless,

00:02:56.150 --> 00:02:59.120
and leave you in suspense,
but many of us have,

00:02:59.120 --> 00:03:02.480
as we have read news reports
out of this very large

00:03:02.480 --> 00:03:07.650
oil-producing country in the
Middle East, we have wondered,

00:03:07.650 --> 00:03:10.580
is this real, and what does
it actually mean for the women

00:03:10.580 --> 00:03:14.420
on the ground who have
been denied their rights,

00:03:14.420 --> 00:03:16.610
and continue to be
denied their rights,

00:03:16.610 --> 00:03:19.140
and have been for so long?

00:03:19.140 --> 00:03:21.230
She's also, excitingly,
going to use film,

00:03:21.230 --> 00:03:23.870
I think, to bring home the
human stakes of the issues

00:03:23.870 --> 00:03:27.050
that she's describing here.

00:03:27.050 --> 00:03:30.140
After Sarah, we will hear
from Nilufer Gole who's

00:03:30.140 --> 00:03:33.950
a Professor of
Sociology, and she's

00:03:33.950 --> 00:03:35.750
going to discuss,
as I understand it,

00:03:35.750 --> 00:03:39.330
Muslim women in Europe,
focusing on the ideas

00:03:39.330 --> 00:03:41.330
very much at the heart
of this conference, ideas

00:03:41.330 --> 00:03:43.700
about crossing
borders, challenging

00:03:43.700 --> 00:03:49.880
concepts of belonging amid
vast demographic shifts.

00:03:49.880 --> 00:03:53.030
And I think she's going to focus
on the issue of veiling, asking

00:03:53.030 --> 00:03:58.040
whether belonging to a country
requires one to embrace

00:03:58.040 --> 00:04:02.040
the shared norms that have
existed in that country,

00:04:02.040 --> 00:04:04.970
and, I think, is intrigued,
it sounds like from her work,

00:04:04.970 --> 00:04:08.360
at looking at how various
identities are negotiated,

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:12.950
identities related to
faith, related to gender,

00:04:12.950 --> 00:04:17.720
related to politics, how one
negotiates all those in one

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:21.649
being and in one society.

00:04:21.649 --> 00:04:25.490
So I just, before handing
off to our two speakers,

00:04:25.490 --> 00:04:29.480
will make four very brief
points about the United States,

00:04:29.480 --> 00:04:31.400
and issues related
to immigration

00:04:31.400 --> 00:04:33.240
and the themes of this panel.

00:04:33.240 --> 00:04:35.692
And this is not an area on
which I'm an expert, but just

00:04:35.692 --> 00:04:38.150
some food for thought, and I
know that within the audience,

00:04:38.150 --> 00:04:40.340
we have vast amounts
of expertise.

00:04:40.340 --> 00:04:44.150
And I really hope that we
can move relatively briskly

00:04:44.150 --> 00:04:47.210
to the discussion, which
will be very, very rich.

00:04:47.210 --> 00:04:50.330
So the first point
I wanted to make

00:04:50.330 --> 00:04:53.930
is to state the obvious,
which is that currently,

00:04:53.930 --> 00:04:57.470
the concept of citizenship
in the United States

00:04:57.470 --> 00:04:59.780
is a more and more
contested one.

00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:02.420
I think some of the
reflexive understandings

00:05:02.420 --> 00:05:04.820
of what it meant to
be American, what

00:05:04.820 --> 00:05:07.550
the identity of
this country was,

00:05:07.550 --> 00:05:10.220
the standing of the
Statue of Liberty

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:15.920
as a relatively uncontroversial
icon, speaking to that,

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:18.980
those elements of American
identity, all of that

00:05:18.980 --> 00:05:22.880
feels much more up for
grabs than it has certainly

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:23.730
in my lifetime.

00:05:23.730 --> 00:05:26.021
And I should say that I'm an
immigrant to this country.

00:05:26.021 --> 00:05:29.820
I came when I was nine from
the country of Ireland.

00:05:29.820 --> 00:05:33.290
So we have people in
very important offices

00:05:33.290 --> 00:05:35.880
in this land including,
arguably, the most important

00:05:35.880 --> 00:05:39.890
office, creating more
exclusionary identities,

00:05:39.890 --> 00:05:43.490
narrower identities,
shrinking the conception

00:05:43.490 --> 00:05:48.620
of American-ness, and
elevating very specific groups

00:05:48.620 --> 00:05:55.160
of Americans to a privileged,
almost normative, status,

00:05:55.160 --> 00:05:56.510
it feels like.

00:05:56.510 --> 00:06:00.500
And to me, that's, of
course, very, very worrying.

00:06:00.500 --> 00:06:06.200
This is happening not only
through tweets and, again,

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:11.060
people contesting, rhetorically,
conceptions of citizenship

00:06:11.060 --> 00:06:17.030
and American-ness, but also
in the capillaries of the US

00:06:17.030 --> 00:06:18.770
government.

00:06:18.770 --> 00:06:24.860
And the most vivid example of
this, I think, at least lately,

00:06:24.860 --> 00:06:28.310
came just a couple of months
ago when the federal agency that

00:06:28.310 --> 00:06:32.180
issues green cards and
grants citizenship to people

00:06:32.180 --> 00:06:35.300
from foreign countries in
this great country, the United

00:06:35.300 --> 00:06:37.580
States, the United States
Citizenship and Immigration

00:06:37.580 --> 00:06:40.190
Services, who many of us
who come to this country

00:06:40.190 --> 00:06:45.260
have had to process our
applications through--

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:51.440
Until very recently, the
USCIS mission statement

00:06:51.440 --> 00:06:54.020
said that its aim
was to secure, quote,

00:06:54.020 --> 00:06:57.420
America's promise as a nation
of immigrants, end quote.

00:06:57.420 --> 00:06:59.570
Like again, a very
uncontroversial statement,

00:06:59.570 --> 00:07:04.370
but several months ago, it
dropped that characterization,

00:07:04.370 --> 00:07:07.160
and so now it turns out, at
least according to the mission

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:11.744
statement of this agency,
which has such a vital role,

00:07:11.744 --> 00:07:13.910
the mission statement, or
the mission of the agency,

00:07:13.910 --> 00:07:17.060
is no longer to cultivate
the United States

00:07:17.060 --> 00:07:21.177
as a, quote, nation of
immigrants, end quote.

00:07:21.177 --> 00:07:22.760
The second point I
want to make, which

00:07:22.760 --> 00:07:24.980
might seem a little
off topic, but I think

00:07:24.980 --> 00:07:26.630
is extremely
important as we think

00:07:26.630 --> 00:07:30.530
about the future
of this country,

00:07:30.530 --> 00:07:34.760
and the future, I think, of
democracy, and inclusion,

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:37.700
and pluralism
around the world, is

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:41.570
that political party
identification in the United

00:07:41.570 --> 00:07:47.210
States is at its most vehement,
and you might even say,

00:07:47.210 --> 00:07:51.380
virulent pitch at present.

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:54.380
And why is this
relevant for discussions

00:07:54.380 --> 00:07:55.940
of citizenship
and American-ness,

00:07:55.940 --> 00:07:57.320
and boundaries and belonging?

00:07:57.320 --> 00:08:00.170
Because right now,
the biggest predictor

00:08:00.170 --> 00:08:04.550
of where one is likely to fall
on some of the key identity

00:08:04.550 --> 00:08:08.190
issues and policy
issues is, simply,

00:08:08.190 --> 00:08:10.640
what is your political party?

00:08:10.640 --> 00:08:13.070
And I just want to
throw out a few,

00:08:13.070 --> 00:08:17.240
I think, very
disturbing statistics

00:08:17.240 --> 00:08:19.820
that will feel familiar to you.

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:24.140
In 1960, only 5%
of Americans said

00:08:24.140 --> 00:08:28.010
that they would be upset if
their child married someone

00:08:28.010 --> 00:08:30.380
in the other political party.

00:08:30.380 --> 00:08:31.280
That was 5%.

00:08:31.280 --> 00:08:36.740
In 2010, 49% of Republicans
and 33% of Democrats

00:08:36.740 --> 00:08:38.900
said that they would be mad.

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:42.620
That was eight years ago, and
for reasons I don't really

00:08:42.620 --> 00:08:44.810
understand, but
it may have to do

00:08:44.810 --> 00:08:48.750
with not wanting
to know the answer,

00:08:48.750 --> 00:08:53.960
that question has not
been polled since 2010.

00:08:53.960 --> 00:08:55.940
And so all we have
now I can offer

00:08:55.940 --> 00:08:59.990
you to try to capture the
zeitgeist of the moment is,

00:08:59.990 --> 00:09:04.070
according to Pew, last
year, only 9% of Republicans

00:09:04.070 --> 00:09:07.070
and 8% of Democrats say
their spouse is a member

00:09:07.070 --> 00:09:10.250
of the other political party.

00:09:10.250 --> 00:09:13.370
But to put this salience
of political identity

00:09:13.370 --> 00:09:16.880
in some broader
context, arguably,

00:09:16.880 --> 00:09:21.860
to offer some good
news, 88% of Republicans

00:09:21.860 --> 00:09:25.430
and 94% of Democrats
today have no problem

00:09:25.430 --> 00:09:27.970
with interracial marriage.

00:09:27.970 --> 00:09:32.650
So inter-party marriage,
like forget about it,

00:09:32.650 --> 00:09:36.280
but interracial marriage, we've
made at least some strides,

00:09:36.280 --> 00:09:38.440
significant strides.

00:09:38.440 --> 00:09:44.764
And on same-sex marriage, while
it's true 74% of Democrats

00:09:44.764 --> 00:09:45.805
favor same-sex marriage--

00:09:45.805 --> 00:09:48.320
I would have thought that
was even higher, but--

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:51.580
and it's true that only
slightly half of Republicans

00:09:51.580 --> 00:09:54.340
favor same-sex
marriage, the support

00:09:54.340 --> 00:09:56.620
for same-sex marriage
in the GOP has

00:09:56.620 --> 00:09:58.597
tripled over the last decade.

00:09:58.597 --> 00:10:01.180
And I think we can expect those
numbers to continue to cascade

00:10:01.180 --> 00:10:02.930
in the right direction.

00:10:02.930 --> 00:10:06.310
So we're now in this
weird world where

00:10:06.310 --> 00:10:09.730
the salience of our
political identities

00:10:09.730 --> 00:10:14.410
feels more important than
our shared status, let's say,

00:10:14.410 --> 00:10:19.780
as parents or as
siblings, or as citizens,

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:22.700
and what does that
mean for the discussion

00:10:22.700 --> 00:10:25.930
that we'll be having, and
for issues of identity?

00:10:25.930 --> 00:10:29.650
Third point, because I was
asked very specifically to speak

00:10:29.650 --> 00:10:34.840
to this, because it's so in
the news and so heartbreaking,

00:10:34.840 --> 00:10:40.630
but in part I think because
of this more virulent forms

00:10:40.630 --> 00:10:43.960
of what Cass Sunstein,
professor at the law school

00:10:43.960 --> 00:10:46.390
who happens to be my
husband, has introduced

00:10:46.390 --> 00:10:50.710
this term, party-ism,
which I think

00:10:50.710 --> 00:10:52.720
speaks to the
ideology of party-ism.

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:58.240
But with party-ism, and
the widening divisions

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:01.630
between the two
mainstream parties here,

00:11:01.630 --> 00:11:04.870
it's even harder to get
agreement on key immigration

00:11:04.870 --> 00:11:06.530
policy issues.

00:11:06.530 --> 00:11:09.160
And so Exhibit A
of that right now

00:11:09.160 --> 00:11:12.910
is what you all know
as the DACA program.

00:11:12.910 --> 00:11:14.050
So the DACA program--

00:11:14.050 --> 00:11:17.710
DACA stands for Deferred
Action for Childhood Arrivals.

00:11:17.710 --> 00:11:19.210
I'm no expert on DACA.

00:11:19.210 --> 00:11:21.770
We we're going to have a great
expert on DACA on the panel.

00:11:21.770 --> 00:11:24.311
Maybe there are people in the
audience who want to speak more

00:11:24.311 --> 00:11:26.650
to this when we open it up.

00:11:26.650 --> 00:11:29.470
But what a
heartbreaking situation

00:11:29.470 --> 00:11:32.530
we find ourselves
in here, not only

00:11:32.530 --> 00:11:35.620
because there are 800,000
people who came to this country

00:11:35.620 --> 00:11:39.700
before they were 16 years old,
and received this protected

00:11:39.700 --> 00:11:44.230
status, and now are living
in terror, associated

00:11:44.230 --> 00:11:46.600
with living in limbo.

00:11:46.600 --> 00:11:50.680
It is true that, for now, the
Department of Homeland Security

00:11:50.680 --> 00:11:53.990
is saying that these people
will not be deported.

00:11:53.990 --> 00:11:56.240
But it is also the
case that their status,

00:11:56.240 --> 00:11:58.870
their protected
status, is expiring.

00:11:58.870 --> 00:12:02.920
Every month, some new batch
in the 800,000, their status

00:12:02.920 --> 00:12:05.740
expires, and what happens
when your status expires?

00:12:05.740 --> 00:12:10.012
Your ability to get a work
permit dramatically diminishes.

00:12:10.012 --> 00:12:12.470
And to give you a sense, again,
and all this is in the news

00:12:12.470 --> 00:12:14.011
and most of you are
familiar with it,

00:12:14.011 --> 00:12:17.860
but this is a
population, those who

00:12:17.860 --> 00:12:23.080
had been DACA recipients, that
are 90% of whom are employed

00:12:23.080 --> 00:12:26.520
or in school, so very
embedded, I mean,

00:12:26.520 --> 00:12:29.770
completely embedded, given
when many of them came.

00:12:29.770 --> 00:12:34.240
The average age in which this
population came to the United

00:12:34.240 --> 00:12:37.810
States, according to the
recipients who were surveyed,

00:12:37.810 --> 00:12:40.150
was six and a half years old.

00:12:40.150 --> 00:12:43.480
And we've all seen the
stories about three-month-olds

00:12:43.480 --> 00:12:45.490
and two-year-olds,
and so forth, who've

00:12:45.490 --> 00:12:47.620
never even been to the
country that they're at risk

00:12:47.620 --> 00:12:49.350
of getting deported to.

00:12:49.350 --> 00:12:53.770
Now why is this Exhibit A
of the political challenges

00:12:53.770 --> 00:12:55.420
associated with these debates?

00:12:55.420 --> 00:12:58.180
Because this is
actually something

00:12:58.180 --> 00:13:01.900
that polls well,
across party lines.

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:06.850
Now unfortunately, each month
that we go without accord,

00:13:06.850 --> 00:13:10.000
the polling gets slightly worse.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:13.630
But as of January of this
year, 87% of Americans

00:13:13.630 --> 00:13:18.790
supported giving protected
status, maintaining, basically,

00:13:18.790 --> 00:13:22.005
this program, to the
Dreamers, as they're called.

00:13:22.005 --> 00:13:23.880
And there's another
million people apparently

00:13:23.880 --> 00:13:25.750
who are eligible for this
program who are not actually

00:13:25.750 --> 00:13:27.790
in the program, also
at risk of deportation

00:13:27.790 --> 00:13:29.600
right now, as we speak.

00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:32.620
But of that 87%, that
was as of January--

00:13:32.620 --> 00:13:37.360
79% Republicans and 92% of
Democrats, and those polls

00:13:37.360 --> 00:13:39.670
are going up on the Democratic
side, and a little bit

00:13:39.670 --> 00:13:42.880
down on the Republican side,
but still well within reach.

00:13:42.880 --> 00:13:47.470
And yet, even on this relatively
non-controversial issue

00:13:47.470 --> 00:13:52.750
of immigration-- never mind
a big comprehensive package

00:13:52.750 --> 00:13:55.360
of reforms that are actually
needed in this country to give

00:13:55.360 --> 00:13:58.570
people the ability to live
in security and in dignity,

00:13:58.570 --> 00:14:02.000
and to get the balance right
in terms of open borders,

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.680
but also being a
nation of immigrants,

00:14:05.680 --> 00:14:08.650
and caring for vulnerable
people around the world--

00:14:08.650 --> 00:14:11.500
getting that balance
right requires

00:14:11.500 --> 00:14:14.530
functional institutions that
can actually cooperate on issues

00:14:14.530 --> 00:14:16.810
around which,
especially, you have what

00:14:16.810 --> 00:14:20.470
passes for a domestic
political consensus.

00:14:20.470 --> 00:14:23.260
And yet, Trump announced
the end of the program

00:14:23.260 --> 00:14:28.440
on September 5th last year,
gave a deadline until March 5th.

00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:31.740
There have been now six
bipartisan proposals

00:14:31.740 --> 00:14:36.010
that have come to him, and
he has rejected all of them,

00:14:36.010 --> 00:14:39.000
including one that would
have given him $25 billion

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.320
for his wall.

00:14:41.320 --> 00:14:42.990
So go figure.

00:14:42.990 --> 00:14:47.250
But if we can't reach agreement
on an issue like that, where

00:14:47.250 --> 00:14:50.310
there's still relative
consensus in the main,

00:14:50.310 --> 00:14:56.010
it's going to be extremely
challenging to reaffirm,

00:14:56.010 --> 00:14:57.990
at least, even the
notion of American-ness,

00:14:57.990 --> 00:15:01.860
even if it was always something
observed in the breach,

00:15:01.860 --> 00:15:04.320
and not consistently
applied across time.

00:15:04.320 --> 00:15:06.497
But now, we even
have divisions again

00:15:06.497 --> 00:15:07.830
on what it means to be American.

00:15:07.830 --> 00:15:12.780
My last point, before
opening it up to our experts,

00:15:12.780 --> 00:15:17.040
is just to make the, again,
very, very obvious point

00:15:17.040 --> 00:15:20.400
about the importance of
politics in all of this.

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:24.270
And it's challenging
because, as you see even

00:15:24.270 --> 00:15:26.040
in the controversy
now associated

00:15:26.040 --> 00:15:29.880
with the census, when you
live in fear, when you are not

00:15:29.880 --> 00:15:34.770
made to feel fully American or a
welcomed member of our society,

00:15:34.770 --> 00:15:38.400
the instinct is to lay
low, and to stay out

00:15:38.400 --> 00:15:42.300
of politics, and to not be
somebody who puts your head up.

00:15:42.300 --> 00:15:44.820
And yet what we, of
course, all need to do

00:15:44.820 --> 00:15:48.570
is mobilize on behalf of
our brothers and sisters.

00:15:48.570 --> 00:15:50.670
And here, for all
of the bad news,

00:15:50.670 --> 00:15:53.880
some of which I have spoken to
in terms of our polarization,

00:15:53.880 --> 00:15:59.010
in terms of our inability to get
things done in order to improve

00:15:59.010 --> 00:16:01.200
the lives of people who
are living in our midst

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:05.340
and are integral to our
country, and our communities,

00:16:05.340 --> 00:16:10.140
the activation, that the
denial of these rights

00:16:10.140 --> 00:16:15.210
and the stripping of the
dignity of so many individuals--

00:16:15.210 --> 00:16:18.720
the activation that is
happening in response to that

00:16:18.720 --> 00:16:20.370
is a sight to behold.

00:16:20.370 --> 00:16:24.450
And I think I want to
close just these opening

00:16:24.450 --> 00:16:28.200
comments by bringing us
back to Louis Brandeis'

00:16:28.200 --> 00:16:30.780
great line, which
is that the most

00:16:30.780 --> 00:16:32.820
important office
in any democracy

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:35.370
is not that of president,
but that of citizen.

00:16:35.370 --> 00:16:37.290
And those of us who
have the privilege

00:16:37.290 --> 00:16:42.700
of being able to live as
citizens, not in the shadows,

00:16:42.700 --> 00:16:45.180
we also have a
responsibility to look out

00:16:45.180 --> 00:16:49.470
for those who are living
in very, very difficult

00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:51.090
dark circumstances right now.

00:16:51.090 --> 00:16:54.630
It is our responsibility
to exercise

00:16:54.630 --> 00:16:57.870
the privilege of citizenship
on behalf of those who

00:16:57.870 --> 00:17:00.490
need support and solidarity.

00:17:00.490 --> 00:17:02.910
So with that, touching
on America as best

00:17:02.910 --> 00:17:05.520
I can, despite being a
foreign policy person,

00:17:05.520 --> 00:17:08.562
I will now turn the
floor over to Sarah,

00:17:08.562 --> 00:17:10.020
and we're very much
looking forward

00:17:10.020 --> 00:17:11.790
to hearing about
that unnamed country

00:17:11.790 --> 00:17:13.781
where a few things have
been happening lately.

00:17:13.781 --> 00:17:14.280
Thank you.

00:17:19.520 --> 00:17:20.970
- Hi, everyone.

00:17:20.970 --> 00:17:22.010
Thanks.

00:17:22.010 --> 00:17:25.079
Thanks for coming.

00:17:25.079 --> 00:17:28.430
It's interesting
that here in 2018,

00:17:28.430 --> 00:17:30.350
the topic of women
in the Middle East

00:17:30.350 --> 00:17:33.320
is actually one of the few
sources of good news coming

00:17:33.320 --> 00:17:35.366
from the region.

00:17:35.366 --> 00:17:36.740
Although women in
the Middle East

00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:40.140
face some of the worst systemic
discrimination in the world,

00:17:40.140 --> 00:17:44.180
we've seen so many advances
with respect to women's rights,

00:17:44.180 --> 00:17:46.590
not just since the
2011 uprisings,

00:17:46.590 --> 00:17:50.360
but really in the
past two decades.

00:17:50.360 --> 00:17:52.730
And indeed, despite the
chaos and catastrophe

00:17:52.730 --> 00:17:58.010
of so many wars in the region,
where countries are not in war,

00:17:58.010 --> 00:17:59.900
we've seen so much
progress, primarily

00:17:59.900 --> 00:18:03.380
in the role of legislation
designed to end discrimination

00:18:03.380 --> 00:18:05.810
against women, or create
protections for them

00:18:05.810 --> 00:18:08.300
from violence and labor abuse.

00:18:08.300 --> 00:18:10.940
Most recently, Lebanon,
Jordan, and Tunisia

00:18:10.940 --> 00:18:14.570
abolished the infamous
'marry your rapist' laws

00:18:14.570 --> 00:18:19.700
which allows a rapist to avoid
jail if he marries his victim.

00:18:19.700 --> 00:18:22.850
Tunisia allowed women to pass
nationality to their children,

00:18:22.850 --> 00:18:24.560
becoming the eighth
country in the region

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:27.020
to allow women to do this.

00:18:27.020 --> 00:18:29.300
Qatar approved a law
that allows children

00:18:29.300 --> 00:18:31.730
born to Qatari women
and non-Qatari fathers

00:18:31.730 --> 00:18:36.660
to at least obtain residency
rights and identification.

00:18:36.660 --> 00:18:41.040
Morocco, Tunisia, and Algeria
passed domestic violence laws,

00:18:41.040 --> 00:18:43.950
and Kuwait, Qatar,
the UAE, and Morocco

00:18:43.950 --> 00:18:45.407
passed domestic worker laws.

00:18:45.407 --> 00:18:46.740
These were just the most recent.

00:18:46.740 --> 00:18:48.780
There are many more examples.

00:18:48.780 --> 00:18:52.410
There are ongoing campaigns
across the region on these

00:18:52.410 --> 00:18:54.240
and other discriminatory
laws, and I

00:18:54.240 --> 00:18:57.360
expect we'll see further
advances as women

00:18:57.360 --> 00:19:01.440
redefine their status as
citizens, not subjects, who

00:19:01.440 --> 00:19:05.040
have and demand the same rights
as women across the world.

00:19:05.040 --> 00:19:08.370
The cultural exceptionalism,
religious exceptionalism,

00:19:08.370 --> 00:19:11.070
arguments are just
not persuasive

00:19:11.070 --> 00:19:16.080
to the female or male youth
bulge in these countries.

00:19:16.080 --> 00:19:19.410
First, before I get to the
main topic of the country that

00:19:19.410 --> 00:19:21.150
hasn't been named,
I want to focus

00:19:21.150 --> 00:19:24.216
on two areas of very
positive development, which

00:19:24.216 --> 00:19:25.590
I think really
touch on the theme

00:19:25.590 --> 00:19:29.890
today of borders and nationality
as they affect gender issues.

00:19:29.890 --> 00:19:31.420
As I mentioned, the
nationality laws

00:19:31.420 --> 00:19:34.030
are a topic of renewed
interest, particularly

00:19:34.030 --> 00:19:36.160
with Tunisia's recent
law allowing women

00:19:36.160 --> 00:19:39.980
to pass nationality
to their children,

00:19:39.980 --> 00:19:42.040
as well as to end
the decree that

00:19:42.040 --> 00:19:46.450
banned or prohibited
Muslim women from marrying

00:19:46.450 --> 00:19:48.160
non-Muslim men.

00:19:48.160 --> 00:19:50.500
Most recently, in
February, the Arab League,

00:19:50.500 --> 00:19:52.600
for the first time,
passed a resolution

00:19:52.600 --> 00:19:55.390
that calls on member
states to, and I'm quoting,

00:19:55.390 --> 00:19:58.120
"End all forms of
discrimination in nationality,

00:19:58.120 --> 00:20:01.720
and to take concrete steps
to amend laws and legislation

00:20:01.720 --> 00:20:03.940
relating to
nationality, in order

00:20:03.940 --> 00:20:06.670
to grant women and men
equal rights in conferring

00:20:06.670 --> 00:20:09.160
nationality to their
children and spouses,

00:20:09.160 --> 00:20:12.310
and to acquire change
or retain nationality."

00:20:12.310 --> 00:20:15.010
This is a very big deal
because, as I mentioned,

00:20:15.010 --> 00:20:17.440
only seven, now eight,
of 20 Arab states

00:20:17.440 --> 00:20:20.650
allow women to pass nationality
on to their children.

00:20:20.650 --> 00:20:23.950
Algeria, Egypt, Morocco,
Tunisia, and Yemen,

00:20:23.950 --> 00:20:27.760
which have always been among the
most progressive with respect

00:20:27.760 --> 00:20:31.480
to women's rights, all provide
equal rights to women and men

00:20:31.480 --> 00:20:33.940
to confer citizenship
to their children.

00:20:33.940 --> 00:20:36.730
Iraq, a remnant from
the Ba'athist era--

00:20:36.730 --> 00:20:39.520
secular laws in
Mauritania, also allow

00:20:39.520 --> 00:20:42.040
women with foreign husbands
to confer nationality

00:20:42.040 --> 00:20:45.140
to their children, if
they're born in the country.

00:20:45.140 --> 00:20:47.860
But for the rest, what this
means is that children,

00:20:47.860 --> 00:20:52.180
and there are millions of them,
born to women, born to citizen

00:20:52.180 --> 00:20:57.040
women married to non-nationals,
do not obtain citizenship

00:20:57.040 --> 00:20:59.890
or nationality,
and in many cases,

00:20:59.890 --> 00:21:02.440
don't have even residency
or rights in the state

00:21:02.440 --> 00:21:03.170
where they live.

00:21:03.170 --> 00:21:04.360
So they can't work.

00:21:04.360 --> 00:21:06.430
They can't study.

00:21:06.430 --> 00:21:10.100
They can't travel, and so forth.

00:21:10.100 --> 00:21:13.340
In Israel, this is enforced
through a so-called family

00:21:13.340 --> 00:21:16.490
reunification law, which is
actually a family division

00:21:16.490 --> 00:21:20.420
law, that prevents spouses
from the occupied territories,

00:21:20.420 --> 00:21:24.770
or states identified as
enemies, like Lebanon and Syria,

00:21:24.770 --> 00:21:26.870
from living in Israel.

00:21:26.870 --> 00:21:29.870
In contrast, Jewish
foreign spouses

00:21:29.870 --> 00:21:32.090
get automatic citizenship.

00:21:32.090 --> 00:21:34.760
Now one justification for
this is a security one,

00:21:34.760 --> 00:21:38.150
because naturally, spouses
from the occupied Palestinian

00:21:38.150 --> 00:21:41.720
territories are potential
terrorists and threats,

00:21:41.720 --> 00:21:43.670
but the real excuse
for these nationality

00:21:43.670 --> 00:21:46.790
laws throughout the
region are, in fact,

00:21:46.790 --> 00:21:49.340
demographic and
political in nature,

00:21:49.340 --> 00:21:51.800
to prevent, for example,
an increase in the number

00:21:51.800 --> 00:21:54.170
of Palestinians in
Jordan or Lebanon

00:21:54.170 --> 00:21:56.990
or Israel, because
that would disrupt

00:21:56.990 --> 00:21:58.980
the demographic balance.

00:21:58.980 --> 00:22:01.580
Because if all the children
of national Jordanian

00:22:01.580 --> 00:22:05.270
or Lebanese or Israeli women
married to Palestinian men

00:22:05.270 --> 00:22:08.000
had nationality, that
would bring a spike

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:14.330
in the population of this
undesirable nationality.

00:22:14.330 --> 00:22:16.490
Particularly in
Jordan, the argument

00:22:16.490 --> 00:22:18.560
is really not
persuasive at all, given

00:22:18.560 --> 00:22:22.070
that the law permits a
Jordanian man to marry

00:22:22.070 --> 00:22:23.750
as many as four women.

00:22:23.750 --> 00:22:27.470
So a Jordanian national can
marry four Palestinian women,

00:22:27.470 --> 00:22:31.400
have all their children,
including foreign nationals,

00:22:31.400 --> 00:22:35.750
and pass on citizenship to
all of the wives and children.

00:22:35.750 --> 00:22:39.340
But the Jordanian
woman can't do that.

00:22:39.340 --> 00:22:41.620
The discriminatory
system really just ties

00:22:41.620 --> 00:22:44.770
into a very entrenched
patriarchal culture,

00:22:44.770 --> 00:22:48.010
mostly about social control,
and controlling women,

00:22:48.010 --> 00:22:50.290
and controlling who
women can marry,

00:22:50.290 --> 00:22:53.500
preventing them,
discouraging them,

00:22:53.500 --> 00:22:56.020
from marrying foreign husbands.

00:22:56.020 --> 00:22:59.830
And so really it's about
family, tribal, local, community

00:22:59.830 --> 00:23:02.280
control over women.

00:23:02.280 --> 00:23:04.380
The Gulf countries are
a particular problem

00:23:04.380 --> 00:23:06.600
because not only do they
not grant nationality

00:23:06.600 --> 00:23:08.730
to these children, they
also don't allow them

00:23:08.730 --> 00:23:10.620
to have dual nationalities.

00:23:10.620 --> 00:23:12.690
So the result is
that children born

00:23:12.690 --> 00:23:16.200
to GCC mothers and
non-GCC fathers,

00:23:16.200 --> 00:23:20.570
or not from that state,
are effectively stateless.

00:23:20.570 --> 00:23:23.950
Some countries, like
Jordan, have put in laws

00:23:23.950 --> 00:23:25.900
to grant at least
certain benefits

00:23:25.900 --> 00:23:28.030
to non-citizen children
instead of allowing

00:23:28.030 --> 00:23:30.640
them to gain nationality
through their mothers.

00:23:30.640 --> 00:23:32.290
As I mentioned,
most recently, Qatar

00:23:32.290 --> 00:23:34.120
approved a law that
allows children

00:23:34.120 --> 00:23:37.300
born to Qatari women
and non-Qatari fathers

00:23:37.300 --> 00:23:39.910
to at least obtain residency
rights and identification

00:23:39.910 --> 00:23:40.960
cards.

00:23:40.960 --> 00:23:43.090
But these half-baked
measures don't work,

00:23:43.090 --> 00:23:45.700
and they continue to relegate
children in such situations

00:23:45.700 --> 00:23:48.170
to second-class status.

00:23:48.170 --> 00:23:50.840
This month, in a couple
of weeks actually,

00:23:50.840 --> 00:23:53.360
we'll launch a new
report in Jordan,

00:23:53.360 --> 00:23:57.020
documenting how the
355,000 stateless children

00:23:57.020 --> 00:24:00.380
of Jordanian mothers
married to non-Jordanians,

00:24:00.380 --> 00:24:04.910
mostly Palestinian, but also
Egyptian, Iraqi, and so forth,

00:24:04.910 --> 00:24:09.630
don't even benefit from the
proposed minimal protections.

00:24:09.630 --> 00:24:12.090
Jordanian authorities restrict
the rights of these children

00:24:12.090 --> 00:24:15.630
to work, own property,
travel to and from Jordan,

00:24:15.630 --> 00:24:18.480
enroll in higher education,
and get government health

00:24:18.480 --> 00:24:21.170
care and other services.

00:24:21.170 --> 00:24:23.920
The 2014 decision that
was purported to ease

00:24:23.920 --> 00:24:25.610
these restrictions
has completely

00:24:25.610 --> 00:24:28.190
fallen short of
expectations, and people

00:24:28.190 --> 00:24:33.250
who are even supposed to be able
to get ID cards can't get them.

00:24:33.250 --> 00:24:35.470
We're working very closely
with women's rights

00:24:35.470 --> 00:24:38.530
activists in Jordan to a joint
campaign to lobby on these laws

00:24:38.530 --> 00:24:40.990
because we think Jordan is
the next best place to get

00:24:40.990 --> 00:24:42.670
these laws overturned.

00:24:42.670 --> 00:24:46.270
But we know it will
be a tough slog.

00:24:46.270 --> 00:24:48.880
I should note that Qatar's
recent change of granting

00:24:48.880 --> 00:24:52.720
residency to children
born to non-Qatari fathers

00:24:52.720 --> 00:24:55.540
was very much precipitated
by the crisis in the country

00:24:55.540 --> 00:24:58.750
due to the siege imposed
by neighboring GCC states.

00:24:58.750 --> 00:25:01.060
So in this case, it
was a security crisis

00:25:01.060 --> 00:25:03.280
that actually created a
motivation and impetus

00:25:03.280 --> 00:25:05.230
for the government
to allow women

00:25:05.230 --> 00:25:08.350
to have their children
get at least residency,

00:25:08.350 --> 00:25:10.360
because stateless
children born in Qatar

00:25:10.360 --> 00:25:14.020
were required, under the laws
of Saudi, and UAE, and Bahrain,

00:25:14.020 --> 00:25:16.600
to return to their
father's national country,

00:25:16.600 --> 00:25:19.660
and had no residency
rights in Qatar.

00:25:19.660 --> 00:25:22.480
We're very hopeful that we will
persuade Qatari authorities

00:25:22.480 --> 00:25:25.000
in this moment of
crisis to actually solve

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:28.180
this problem by allowing Qatari
women to pass nationality

00:25:28.180 --> 00:25:30.910
on to their children.

00:25:30.910 --> 00:25:33.210
A second area of
women's rights issues

00:25:33.210 --> 00:25:35.310
that touches on the
intersection of borders

00:25:35.310 --> 00:25:38.370
and national identity,
quite interestingly,

00:25:38.370 --> 00:25:41.520
is the status of migrant
domestic workers.

00:25:41.520 --> 00:25:44.010
The biggest population of
migrant workers in the Middle

00:25:44.010 --> 00:25:46.750
East are not
construction workers,

00:25:46.750 --> 00:25:49.870
but actually migrant
domestic workers, housemaids,

00:25:49.870 --> 00:25:52.590
three to four million of
them, almost entirely women,

00:25:52.590 --> 00:25:54.990
almost entirely in
the Gulf, but also

00:25:54.990 --> 00:25:58.320
prevalent in Lebanon and Jordan.

00:25:58.320 --> 00:26:02.790
Ten years ago, these workers
had no protection, virtually

00:26:02.790 --> 00:26:05.310
no protection, and
we made exposing

00:26:05.310 --> 00:26:07.230
abuses against migrant
domestic workers

00:26:07.230 --> 00:26:11.610
a major priority of our
work, including, for example,

00:26:11.610 --> 00:26:13.620
the confiscation of
their passports, the fact

00:26:13.620 --> 00:26:15.240
that they owed
$1,000 in recruiting

00:26:15.240 --> 00:26:17.774
fees, the fact that they
couldn't leave their employers,

00:26:17.774 --> 00:26:19.690
the fact that they were
locked in their homes,

00:26:19.690 --> 00:26:22.830
not allowed to leave,
couldn't make phone calls,

00:26:22.830 --> 00:26:27.100
and lived as virtual slaves
in their owners' homes.

00:26:27.100 --> 00:26:29.580
And I didn't use that
term accidentally.

00:26:29.580 --> 00:26:31.470
That is how they were
perceived by the law,

00:26:31.470 --> 00:26:34.380
so that a domestic worker
who fled her employer

00:26:34.380 --> 00:26:36.840
was considered
absconding, running away,

00:26:36.840 --> 00:26:39.720
because she was
owned by her sponsor,

00:26:39.720 --> 00:26:41.580
and her legal presence
in the country

00:26:41.580 --> 00:26:45.165
is bound completely by her
sponsor, who is the employer.

00:26:47.670 --> 00:26:49.950
These are primarily
South Asian women,

00:26:49.950 --> 00:26:52.950
now increasingly East African
women in Arab countries,

00:26:52.950 --> 00:26:57.070
who speak little to no
Arabic, and so, in fact,

00:26:57.070 --> 00:26:58.650
for many years, it
was very difficult

00:26:58.650 --> 00:27:01.470
for us to get women's rights
organizations in the Middle

00:27:01.470 --> 00:27:04.140
East to see the problem of
migrant domestic workers

00:27:04.140 --> 00:27:06.390
as a woman's problem.

00:27:06.390 --> 00:27:09.300
One of the ways we
took on the issue

00:27:09.300 --> 00:27:11.400
was, for example,
making videos that

00:27:11.400 --> 00:27:16.110
showed Kuwaiti women or Lebanese
women dressed in maid costumes

00:27:16.110 --> 00:27:18.540
so that they could
try to identify

00:27:18.540 --> 00:27:21.300
with the situation of these
migrant domestic workers,

00:27:21.300 --> 00:27:25.130
and literally stand
in their shoes.

00:27:25.130 --> 00:27:29.300
It was also a challenge because
most of the actual abuse,

00:27:29.300 --> 00:27:31.160
in many cases even
physical abuse,

00:27:31.160 --> 00:27:34.070
was happening at the hands
of, essentially, women

00:27:34.070 --> 00:27:37.670
bosses in the household.

00:27:37.670 --> 00:27:40.790
But rights for migrant workers,
migrant domestic workers,

00:27:40.790 --> 00:27:45.590
as workers, as employees, as
laborers, not as property,

00:27:45.590 --> 00:27:47.780
was also very much seen
as a security issue

00:27:47.780 --> 00:27:49.940
by the governments
in that granting them

00:27:49.940 --> 00:27:52.130
rights as workers
suggested granting them

00:27:52.130 --> 00:27:54.650
rights as residents,
and could make

00:27:54.650 --> 00:27:57.700
their migrant status permanent.

00:27:57.700 --> 00:28:00.580
We did continue to work to
chip away at these perceptions,

00:28:00.580 --> 00:28:03.302
and slowly, the laws
have started to change,

00:28:03.302 --> 00:28:04.510
and really started to change.

00:28:04.510 --> 00:28:08.380
First, the government started
passing model contracts that

00:28:08.380 --> 00:28:10.930
regulated the number of hours
a migrant worker could work

00:28:10.930 --> 00:28:13.510
a day, that allowed
for time off and breaks

00:28:13.510 --> 00:28:15.760
during the day,
that paid overtime.

00:28:15.760 --> 00:28:19.330
These were completely
foreign concepts, the notion

00:28:19.330 --> 00:28:21.760
that a migrant domestic
worker could have a day off.

00:28:21.760 --> 00:28:23.770
Employers would say they didn't
want her to have a day off

00:28:23.770 --> 00:28:25.420
because that would mean
she would leave the house,

00:28:25.420 --> 00:28:26.800
and get a boyfriend,
and have sex,

00:28:26.800 --> 00:28:28.633
and that's why she
shouldn't have a day off.

00:28:30.910 --> 00:28:32.770
But as these
evolved, soon we were

00:28:32.770 --> 00:28:35.320
able to persuade
governments to actually pass

00:28:35.320 --> 00:28:38.230
migrant domestic worker
laws that, again, regulated

00:28:38.230 --> 00:28:43.000
the status of these workers, the
hours, the pay, and so forth,

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:47.080
leading up to the best law of
all which was Jordan's, which

00:28:47.080 --> 00:28:49.750
actually just put migrant
domestic workers to be covered

00:28:49.750 --> 00:28:52.840
by the regular normal labor
law, which, by the way, even

00:28:52.840 --> 00:28:54.520
US and UK law don't do.

00:28:54.520 --> 00:28:57.610
Migrant domestic workers are not
covered by the labor law that

00:28:57.610 --> 00:29:00.800
applies to all other workers.

00:29:00.800 --> 00:29:02.930
So this was soon
followed, as I said-- now

00:29:02.930 --> 00:29:04.970
Bahrain passed a migrant
domestic worker law.

00:29:04.970 --> 00:29:09.320
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,
Morocco, Qatar, and the UAE

00:29:09.320 --> 00:29:10.860
didn't do it voluntarily.

00:29:10.860 --> 00:29:15.350
They were pushed, and now
Lebanon and Oman, surprisingly,

00:29:15.350 --> 00:29:19.760
disappointingly Lebanon, are
the only two remaining outliers,

00:29:19.760 --> 00:29:21.830
with large migrant worker
populations that have

00:29:21.830 --> 00:29:25.250
no domestic worker regulations.

00:29:25.250 --> 00:29:28.970
So it is an area
of interesting--

00:29:28.970 --> 00:29:31.130
I hate to use the word,
but I will-- intersection

00:29:31.130 --> 00:29:33.987
between women and their
nationality and their gender

00:29:33.987 --> 00:29:35.570
identity, and how
that determines what

00:29:35.570 --> 00:29:38.940
they see as women's issues.

00:29:38.940 --> 00:29:40.820
But what I really want
to focus my remarks

00:29:40.820 --> 00:29:47.020
on today is how we, I, Human
Rights Watch, as a western,

00:29:47.020 --> 00:29:49.790
albeit international, as
we keep telling people,

00:29:49.790 --> 00:29:52.880
human rights organization
has pursued women's rights

00:29:52.880 --> 00:29:56.840
advocacy in partnership
across the borders

00:29:56.840 --> 00:29:58.760
with women activists
and women's rights

00:29:58.760 --> 00:30:02.360
organizations in the
region, as a model for,

00:30:02.360 --> 00:30:04.970
I hope, how we can overcome
some of the challenges

00:30:04.970 --> 00:30:07.730
that any advocacy on women's
rights in the Muslim world

00:30:07.730 --> 00:30:11.960
or Arab world often faces,
that this sort of advocacy,

00:30:11.960 --> 00:30:14.660
that this notion of rights
are western in position,

00:30:14.660 --> 00:30:18.260
that they're colonial,
that they're imperialist.

00:30:18.260 --> 00:30:20.970
And I want to delve into
our work on Saudi Arabia--

00:30:20.970 --> 00:30:25.310
surprise-- where we've invested
over a decade of research

00:30:25.310 --> 00:30:27.650
and advocacy to tackle
the so-called guardianship

00:30:27.650 --> 00:30:30.620
system in the country, as well
as a host of other measures

00:30:30.620 --> 00:30:33.260
in the country that
segregate and exclude women

00:30:33.260 --> 00:30:37.160
from normal life experiences
and opportunities.

00:30:37.160 --> 00:30:39.500
So yes, Saudi Arabia has
attracted a great deal

00:30:39.500 --> 00:30:43.100
of attention following dramatic
announcements from the new king

00:30:43.100 --> 00:30:45.800
and the now-famous
young crown prince--

00:30:45.800 --> 00:30:48.830
this week, it's on the cover
of Time Magazine-- promising

00:30:48.830 --> 00:30:52.340
significant reforms for
women's rights and inclusion.

00:30:52.340 --> 00:30:54.200
The government's promised
to reform aspects

00:30:54.200 --> 00:30:56.900
of its guardianship system,
allow women to drive,

00:30:56.900 --> 00:30:59.600
open up job sectors
previously excluded to women,

00:30:59.600 --> 00:31:02.190
allow women to attend
sporting events,

00:31:02.190 --> 00:31:04.460
implement sports
education for girls,

00:31:04.460 --> 00:31:06.950
and further limit the
power of religious police

00:31:06.950 --> 00:31:09.320
who have, for decades,
harassed, attacked,

00:31:09.320 --> 00:31:12.380
and beaten women for
perceived morality crimes,

00:31:12.380 --> 00:31:15.640
like a bad hijab.

00:31:15.640 --> 00:31:19.060
We have yet to see these
promised reforms materialize,

00:31:19.060 --> 00:31:21.790
but the circumstances that led
to the government prioritizing

00:31:21.790 --> 00:31:24.770
these reforms didn't
happen overnight.

00:31:24.770 --> 00:31:27.236
As I think every woman
activist here knows,

00:31:27.236 --> 00:31:29.110
the governments take
credit for these things,

00:31:29.110 --> 00:31:32.140
but it's a long hard
slog of women's work

00:31:32.140 --> 00:31:35.170
for many, many years
that produces change.

00:31:35.170 --> 00:31:38.020
And Saudi women activists have
been fighting for many years

00:31:38.020 --> 00:31:41.890
to challenge what is undoubtedly
the most regressive regime

00:31:41.890 --> 00:31:46.090
of the region, and face terrible
repression and persecution,

00:31:46.090 --> 00:31:50.050
including long jail
sentences as a result.

00:31:50.050 --> 00:31:52.830
So this also follows, as I
said, a decade of research

00:31:52.830 --> 00:31:55.500
and advocacy from Human
Rights Watch on every aspect

00:31:55.500 --> 00:31:58.320
of the newly promised reforms.

00:31:58.320 --> 00:32:00.720
In 2008, we produced
our first report

00:32:00.720 --> 00:32:03.480
on the guardianship system
which, in case you don't know,

00:32:03.480 --> 00:32:07.120
requires every woman to have
a male guardian, a father,

00:32:07.120 --> 00:32:08.820
a brother, a
husband, even a son,

00:32:08.820 --> 00:32:12.120
no matter how old she
is, who has the authority

00:32:12.120 --> 00:32:15.400
to make a range of critical
decisions on her behalf,

00:32:15.400 --> 00:32:17.580
including whether she
can apply for a passport,

00:32:17.580 --> 00:32:19.950
travel outside the
country, study abroad

00:32:19.950 --> 00:32:24.270
on government scholarship,
get married, or leave prison.

00:32:24.270 --> 00:32:27.030
Saudi women regularly
face difficulty, if not

00:32:27.030 --> 00:32:30.360
the impossibility, of conducting
a range of transactions

00:32:30.360 --> 00:32:33.300
from renting an apartment
to filing a legal claim,

00:32:33.300 --> 00:32:35.790
even to obtaining
medical treatment

00:32:35.790 --> 00:32:39.450
without a male relative's
consent or presence.

00:32:39.450 --> 00:32:42.900
So our first report on
this subject in 2008

00:32:42.900 --> 00:32:46.430
was pathbreaking, at
least for us, I think,

00:32:46.430 --> 00:32:49.050
and people who work in this,
because it was the first time

00:32:49.050 --> 00:32:52.530
to document the voices and
testimonies of Saudi women,

00:32:52.530 --> 00:32:55.860
Saudi children, Saudi
families, in Arabic,

00:32:55.860 --> 00:32:58.450
on how the guardianship system
was affecting their lives.

00:32:58.450 --> 00:33:00.330
So this wasn't us
telling everybody

00:33:00.330 --> 00:33:03.030
in Saudi Arabia what's wrong
with the guardianship system.

00:33:03.030 --> 00:33:07.170
It was Saudi women talking about
how this system was ruining

00:33:07.170 --> 00:33:09.670
their lives,
including, for example,

00:33:09.670 --> 00:33:11.940
a woman who was unable to
get a hysterectomy, which

00:33:11.940 --> 00:33:14.430
she urgently needed, because
her male guardian would not

00:33:14.430 --> 00:33:16.560
consent.

00:33:16.560 --> 00:33:19.380
In part in response
to this, and that sort

00:33:19.380 --> 00:33:21.810
of international attention
it brought, the government

00:33:21.810 --> 00:33:23.880
made promises at the
Human Rights Council,

00:33:23.880 --> 00:33:28.260
first in 2009, then in 2013,
to abolish the guardianship

00:33:28.260 --> 00:33:29.405
system.

00:33:29.405 --> 00:33:30.780
At the same time,
of course, they

00:33:30.780 --> 00:33:33.090
were saying that they didn't
have a guardianship system,

00:33:33.090 --> 00:33:35.298
and that what they had was
a system where women could

00:33:35.298 --> 00:33:38.160
do a lot of things, except
when they needed protection

00:33:38.160 --> 00:33:41.160
from a male guardian who was
only trying to protect her.

00:33:41.160 --> 00:33:44.220
But they eased and soon
abolished most of the labor law

00:33:44.220 --> 00:33:47.340
restrictions that required
male permission to work,

00:33:47.340 --> 00:33:49.770
but they did little to
nothing to sanction employers

00:33:49.770 --> 00:33:52.500
that continued to require it.

00:33:52.500 --> 00:33:54.330
In education,
various universities

00:33:54.330 --> 00:33:57.780
started to abolish the guardian
permission requirement.

00:33:57.780 --> 00:34:00.630
In 2014, divorced women
were allowed to register

00:34:00.630 --> 00:34:03.010
their children in schools--
before they couldn't.

00:34:03.010 --> 00:34:06.390
In 2016, divorced
or widowed women,

00:34:06.390 --> 00:34:09.300
women without a guardian,
could obtain their own identity

00:34:09.300 --> 00:34:13.730
cards which was necessary to
access any social service.

00:34:13.730 --> 00:34:16.215
We turned to sports
next, because we

00:34:16.215 --> 00:34:17.840
thought the moment
was ripe, with Saudi

00:34:17.840 --> 00:34:21.350
joining the five-member
Olympic commission for the 2012

00:34:21.350 --> 00:34:22.340
Olympics.

00:34:22.340 --> 00:34:24.080
And we focused on the
exclusion of women

00:34:24.080 --> 00:34:26.330
from the Saudi
Olympic delegation,

00:34:26.330 --> 00:34:29.540
and pressured them to
finally include Saudi women

00:34:29.540 --> 00:34:32.150
in their team in
the 2012 Olympics,

00:34:32.150 --> 00:34:35.060
as well as to promise to
allow girls sports education

00:34:35.060 --> 00:34:39.020
in schools, previously not
allowed in public schools

00:34:39.020 --> 00:34:42.980
because it might, in the
words of one Saudi cleric,

00:34:42.980 --> 00:34:45.370
damage their virginity.

00:34:45.370 --> 00:34:49.130
But Saudi women watching
Saudi athletes on television

00:34:49.130 --> 00:34:51.770
at the London Olympics,
waving the Saudi flag,

00:34:51.770 --> 00:34:54.139
said it was the happiest
day in their lives

00:34:54.139 --> 00:34:58.550
to see themselves represented
in an international scale.

00:34:58.550 --> 00:35:01.700
So in 2016, we decided
to launch an update

00:35:01.700 --> 00:35:04.460
to highlight these
reforms, but also wanted

00:35:04.460 --> 00:35:06.710
to really push to
eliminate this guardianship

00:35:06.710 --> 00:35:09.200
system in its entirety.

00:35:09.200 --> 00:35:13.030
We launched an 80-page
report, and three short videos

00:35:13.030 --> 00:35:14.830
which you'll see
later, that aimed

00:35:14.830 --> 00:35:16.960
at highlighting the
continued application

00:35:16.960 --> 00:35:19.390
of this discriminatory system.

00:35:19.390 --> 00:35:22.270
But this time, more
than any prior time,

00:35:22.270 --> 00:35:24.790
we decided to partner
very, very closely

00:35:24.790 --> 00:35:26.560
with a number of
incredible Saudi women

00:35:26.560 --> 00:35:29.530
activists and
influential commentators,

00:35:29.530 --> 00:35:31.390
because we wanted
to be persuasive,

00:35:31.390 --> 00:35:34.060
we wanted to be effective, we
wanted people in Saudi Arabia

00:35:34.060 --> 00:35:39.170
to actually hear us and not just
hear voices that we scripted,

00:35:39.170 --> 00:35:45.170
but hear issues in a narrative
that was persuasive, locally.

00:35:45.170 --> 00:35:49.780
And so we consulted with these
activists and commentators

00:35:49.780 --> 00:35:52.430
on every aspect of our
research and advocacy,

00:35:52.430 --> 00:35:54.790
the videos, the
recommendations in the report,

00:35:54.790 --> 00:35:56.560
and the strategy we
we're going to use

00:35:56.560 --> 00:35:59.230
to ensure that the report
got traction in Saudi Arabia

00:35:59.230 --> 00:36:00.800
itself.

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:04.425
So for example, we originally
demanded, as a recommendation

00:36:04.425 --> 00:36:08.170
in our report, a complete
end to sex segregation,

00:36:08.170 --> 00:36:10.990
particularly in the workplace
where this is a huge problem.

00:36:10.990 --> 00:36:14.180
But our Saudi partners
advised against it.

00:36:14.180 --> 00:36:16.390
So instead, we asked
the Ministry of Labor

00:36:16.390 --> 00:36:19.210
to abolish registries
of companies

00:36:19.210 --> 00:36:20.800
that don't sex segregate.

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:23.830
It was a more modest
ask, but it was one

00:36:23.830 --> 00:36:27.600
that they felt would effectively
address much of their problem.

00:36:27.600 --> 00:36:31.060
It would end the
stigmatization of employers

00:36:31.060 --> 00:36:33.280
that did not segregate.

00:36:33.280 --> 00:36:36.400
Saudi activists spent hours
working with us on the videos,

00:36:36.400 --> 00:36:38.650
and went back and forth
on specific details

00:36:38.650 --> 00:36:41.830
about what would make it seem
authentic to a Saudi audience,

00:36:41.830 --> 00:36:44.920
what the hashtags should be,
what the tag lines should be,

00:36:44.920 --> 00:36:47.070
and we agreed it
would be Together

00:36:47.070 --> 00:36:49.600
To End Male Guardianship.

00:36:49.600 --> 00:36:52.270
We interviewed Saudi
business women, artists,

00:36:52.270 --> 00:36:54.610
and commentators, to see
what narrative they thought

00:36:54.610 --> 00:36:57.460
would be most effective
in the videos,

00:36:57.460 --> 00:37:01.690
and we spent months teeing
up the report and the videos

00:37:01.690 --> 00:37:03.430
with prominent commentators.

00:37:03.430 --> 00:37:05.170
Saudi Arabia has
the deepest Twitter

00:37:05.170 --> 00:37:09.730
saturation rate pro capite
in the world, large groups

00:37:09.730 --> 00:37:12.790
on Telegram and
Facebook, asking them

00:37:12.790 --> 00:37:15.880
to put their own spin on
the issue, on the report,

00:37:15.880 --> 00:37:17.680
on the commentary.

00:37:17.680 --> 00:37:20.470
So I want to play these
very short videos for you

00:37:20.470 --> 00:37:23.230
now, so you get a
flavor of how we tried

00:37:23.230 --> 00:37:27.400
to communicate on this issue.

00:37:27.400 --> 00:37:43.030
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:37:43.030 --> 00:37:43.660
- Look.

00:37:43.660 --> 00:37:46.035
The best thing you can do is
reconcile with your husband.

00:38:27.600 --> 00:38:28.900
- She brought shame upon us.

00:38:28.900 --> 00:38:30.525
There's no way I can
let her come home.

00:39:43.169 --> 00:39:51.630
[END PLAYBACK]

00:39:51.630 --> 00:39:55.770
- So together, the video has
garnered 2 and 1/2 million

00:39:55.770 --> 00:40:00.150
views on Facebook, and
270,000 more on YouTube

00:40:00.150 --> 00:40:03.330
within the first 72
hours of their release.

00:40:03.330 --> 00:40:09.110
Our hashtag campaign, Together
To End Male Guardianship--

00:40:09.110 --> 00:40:12.550
a little help in the slide.

00:40:12.550 --> 00:40:13.220
Got it?

00:40:13.220 --> 00:40:19.850
Yeah-- inspired Saudi activists
to launch their own grassroots

00:40:19.850 --> 00:40:23.710
campaign two weeks after
our report launched.

00:40:23.710 --> 00:40:26.540
And that was Saudi women--

00:40:26.540 --> 00:40:27.670
sorry, clicking here--

00:40:30.330 --> 00:40:35.130
Saudi women to demand
an end to guardianship.

00:40:35.130 --> 00:40:37.740
Every day, they would add
a number, one, two, three,

00:40:37.740 --> 00:40:39.970
to track each day as
their campaign went on.

00:40:39.970 --> 00:40:42.900
It was trending for three
months in a number of videos

00:40:42.900 --> 00:40:48.540
and social campaigns.

00:40:48.540 --> 00:40:50.940
In a number of the videos,
our report's recommendations

00:40:50.940 --> 00:40:53.220
were copy pasted as the
campaign's demands, which

00:40:53.220 --> 00:40:54.930
was pretty incredible.

00:40:54.930 --> 00:40:57.390
Activists had a sense of
ownership over the campaign

00:40:57.390 --> 00:40:59.880
and tweeted it, and
shared it, as I mentioned.

00:40:59.880 --> 00:41:03.120
The hashtag is still
circulating, apparently even

00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:07.710
graffitied on walls
in Saudi Arabia.

00:41:07.710 --> 00:41:12.900
They posted personal
testimonials online,

00:41:12.900 --> 00:41:16.750
made their own videos,
including a music video,

00:41:16.750 --> 00:41:18.690
which I wish I
could play with you,

00:41:18.690 --> 00:41:22.710
which had 20 million views,
created and distributed

00:41:22.710 --> 00:41:26.430
their own 'I Am My Own
Guardian' bracelets,

00:41:26.430 --> 00:41:30.480
organized the sending of 2,500
messages and a 15,000-signature

00:41:30.480 --> 00:41:34.800
petition to the king, asking him
to dismantle the guardianship

00:41:34.800 --> 00:41:37.495
system, and the petition
was only in Arabic.

00:41:40.280 --> 00:41:43.190
They wrote articles creating
the system, and created art.

00:41:43.190 --> 00:41:45.440
This is Ms. Suffau,
a Saudi artist

00:41:45.440 --> 00:41:47.360
who made t-shirts,
murals and images

00:41:47.360 --> 00:41:50.120
that became the unofficial
symbol of the campaign,

00:41:50.120 --> 00:41:52.880
and which she released
to the public domain.

00:41:52.880 --> 00:41:54.575
The stickers then stuck around.

00:41:57.840 --> 00:42:00.630
Saudi activists,
writers, and academics

00:42:00.630 --> 00:42:04.470
came out, saying women deserve
more independence from men.

00:42:04.470 --> 00:42:07.200
Even though the Grand Mufti
critiqued the campaign,

00:42:07.200 --> 00:42:10.800
other religious officials soon
said that, actually, women

00:42:10.800 --> 00:42:13.120
should be equal.

00:42:13.120 --> 00:42:15.264
Run out of time here,
so maybe in the Q&amp;A,

00:42:15.264 --> 00:42:17.430
I can tell you a little bit
about the current status

00:42:17.430 --> 00:42:19.710
of the promised reforms.

00:42:19.710 --> 00:42:24.420
They're still mostly
promises, but the risks

00:42:24.420 --> 00:42:27.270
for women activists
remain heightened,

00:42:27.270 --> 00:42:30.180
and the campaign has
not been cost free.

00:42:30.180 --> 00:42:32.220
Just one example,
women activists

00:42:32.220 --> 00:42:35.040
received phone calls before
the announcement about women

00:42:35.040 --> 00:42:37.740
driving, telling them
not to speak publicly

00:42:37.740 --> 00:42:39.690
about the end of
the driving ban,

00:42:39.690 --> 00:42:41.970
because the narrative is
that this is a government

00:42:41.970 --> 00:42:43.860
initiative, and that
only the government can

00:42:43.860 --> 00:42:45.900
be an agent of change.

00:42:45.900 --> 00:42:47.890
That's completely false.

00:42:47.890 --> 00:42:48.390
Thank you.

00:42:48.390 --> 00:42:49.515
- Thank you so much, Sarah.

00:42:52.614 --> 00:42:53.580
That's excellent.

