00:42:59.859 --> 00:43:01.100
- Nilufer.

00:43:01.100 --> 00:43:02.010
- I jump.

00:43:02.010 --> 00:43:02.510
OK.

00:43:02.510 --> 00:43:02.870
- Thank you.

00:43:02.870 --> 00:43:03.440
- Thank you.

00:43:03.440 --> 00:43:06.460
Thank you very much
for letting me also

00:43:06.460 --> 00:43:07.820
to join the conversation.

00:43:07.820 --> 00:43:12.630
Now the word conversation is
loaded since the last panel.

00:43:12.630 --> 00:43:16.490
So I was wondering if
I have the courage.

00:43:16.490 --> 00:43:18.380
Is this majority?

00:43:18.380 --> 00:43:18.920
What is it?

00:43:18.920 --> 00:43:21.650
It's every time for a
person, or for a woman,

00:43:21.650 --> 00:43:26.330
it's hard to join the
conversation to synchronize

00:43:26.330 --> 00:43:28.130
our words and perspectives.

00:43:28.130 --> 00:43:33.470
So I will be speaking
about Muslim women,

00:43:33.470 --> 00:43:36.380
but in European contexts,
which is different

00:43:36.380 --> 00:43:40.460
because where there's freedom,
where state doesn't control,

00:43:40.460 --> 00:43:43.070
doesn't take control
over the public life,

00:43:43.070 --> 00:43:47.990
I think this is the difference,
maybe, that I pursue with you,

00:43:47.990 --> 00:43:50.780
how the public sphere
is free, and it becomes

00:43:50.780 --> 00:43:55.190
a very important place of
encounter between Muslim women

00:43:55.190 --> 00:43:55.980
and others.

00:43:55.980 --> 00:44:00.110
This will be the kind of--

00:44:00.110 --> 00:44:04.760
I mean, the realm in which
I'm going to situate my talk.

00:44:04.760 --> 00:44:09.980
And the question that
will lead my talk will be,

00:44:09.980 --> 00:44:14.640
do we have to share the
same norms to belong?

00:44:14.640 --> 00:44:17.300
I think this is just a
simple question, but quite

00:44:17.300 --> 00:44:21.980
complicated, that I'm trying to,
not answer, but at least raise,

00:44:21.980 --> 00:44:25.520
because I think that's what is
going on in European context,

00:44:25.520 --> 00:44:28.910
the question of difference,
this time, difference,

00:44:28.910 --> 00:44:30.680
religious and
cultural, because it's

00:44:30.680 --> 00:44:35.840
hard to make the definition
of Islamic presence in Europe.

00:44:35.840 --> 00:44:36.950
Is it about religion?

00:44:36.950 --> 00:44:38.000
Is it about culture?

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:38.600
It's both.

00:44:41.450 --> 00:44:44.900
I would say it is not
properly addressed

00:44:44.900 --> 00:44:46.940
since the last 20 years.

00:44:46.940 --> 00:44:51.290
We can see the
controversies around Islam

00:44:51.290 --> 00:44:58.520
are debated in a way that
has not provided societies

00:44:58.520 --> 00:45:01.370
with frames of thinking
this difference.

00:45:01.370 --> 00:45:05.010
That will be maybe
the end result,

00:45:05.010 --> 00:45:09.650
which changes or endangers the
pluralistic democracies itself.

00:45:09.650 --> 00:45:15.840
So this is the frame of my talk.

00:45:15.840 --> 00:45:23.300
So the Islamic presence is
basically framed as a problem,

00:45:23.300 --> 00:45:26.670
and we put together many
different problems together.

00:45:26.670 --> 00:45:28.000
That is refugee crisis.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:32.090
It became a crisis
situation, refugee crisis,

00:45:32.090 --> 00:45:36.050
jihadist terrorism,
and Muslim migrants

00:45:36.050 --> 00:45:39.290
living in European
countries, already

00:45:39.290 --> 00:45:41.580
second, third
generation, as citizens.

00:45:41.580 --> 00:45:48.080
So the question of citizenship
are not related in the same way

00:45:48.080 --> 00:45:51.080
to these three groups,
and very often, we

00:45:51.080 --> 00:45:54.980
make this amalgam, as
the French would say,

00:45:54.980 --> 00:45:57.980
the identification between
these three problems

00:45:57.980 --> 00:46:01.160
that are quite
distinct, that also

00:46:01.160 --> 00:46:05.600
overshadows the ordinary Muslims
living in these countries.

00:46:05.600 --> 00:46:08.810
The word ordinary is
also quite a paradox,

00:46:08.810 --> 00:46:12.980
because you cannot be ordinary
if you become visibly Muslim,

00:46:12.980 --> 00:46:15.470
and that is the
real issue today.

00:46:15.470 --> 00:46:18.620
How do you become a citizen,
ordinary citizen, but when

00:46:18.620 --> 00:46:20.960
you are visibly
Muslim, that creates

00:46:20.960 --> 00:46:24.990
some problems, tensions,
conflicts, and even laws

00:46:24.990 --> 00:46:26.290
at the end of the day.

00:46:26.290 --> 00:46:33.370
So basically, I am
thinking about Muslim faith

00:46:33.370 --> 00:46:34.960
in post-migratory faith.

00:46:34.960 --> 00:46:39.100
I say post migratory
because they themselves,

00:46:39.100 --> 00:46:41.590
the youth living
in European cities,

00:46:41.590 --> 00:46:47.620
doesn't want to be identified
as people of migrant origin.

00:46:47.620 --> 00:46:49.990
It is important because
we identify them

00:46:49.990 --> 00:46:53.860
as coming from migrant origins.

00:46:53.860 --> 00:46:57.040
They do not want to be
identified as in relation

00:46:57.040 --> 00:47:01.710
to their parents'
origins, national origins.

00:47:01.710 --> 00:47:05.590
So they do feel belonging
to French society,

00:47:05.590 --> 00:47:07.420
to Germany, to Italy.

00:47:07.420 --> 00:47:09.820
That's something very
important, and we still

00:47:09.820 --> 00:47:13.100
send them to the origins
of their parents.

00:47:13.100 --> 00:47:15.790
So this is their own way
of becoming citizens,

00:47:15.790 --> 00:47:21.100
so this citizenship, but without
giving up Muslim difference.

00:47:21.100 --> 00:47:25.480
Indeed, the way they also
recover or reappropriate

00:47:25.480 --> 00:47:28.360
Muslim religious
markers are quite

00:47:28.360 --> 00:47:30.830
different from their parents.

00:47:30.830 --> 00:47:34.330
So it's something new, because
the conditions of migration

00:47:34.330 --> 00:47:37.836
create a rupture,
a discontinuity,

00:47:37.836 --> 00:47:40.750
in terms of learning
religion, in terms

00:47:40.750 --> 00:47:43.390
of transmission of religion.

00:47:43.390 --> 00:47:47.590
So the ways these Muslim, third,
second, generation of Muslims

00:47:47.590 --> 00:47:50.600
are living their faith
is quite different.

00:47:50.600 --> 00:47:54.170
They are innovating on the
basis of everyday life,

00:47:54.170 --> 00:47:58.570
the way of becoming, the way
how to live their religion

00:47:58.570 --> 00:48:01.270
in a European secular context.

00:48:01.270 --> 00:48:04.150
So it's not a linear
process of integration,

00:48:04.150 --> 00:48:07.350
but we are at the stage
of a certain integration--

00:48:07.350 --> 00:48:10.660
that's why I called it
post-migratory phase--

00:48:10.660 --> 00:48:16.160
that the problems arise,
not because it's a problem.

00:48:16.160 --> 00:48:18.130
But on the contrary,
those Muslims

00:48:18.130 --> 00:48:22.090
who are already successful
in their integration

00:48:22.090 --> 00:48:26.140
create these series
of controversies.

00:48:26.140 --> 00:48:26.640
Why?

00:48:26.640 --> 00:48:31.890
Because the first generation
was very discreet in the ways

00:48:31.890 --> 00:48:35.460
they expressed their
religious difference.

00:48:35.460 --> 00:48:37.440
They kept it at home.

00:48:37.440 --> 00:48:39.600
They didn't show it publicly.

00:48:39.600 --> 00:48:43.380
So the second, third generation
post-migratory phase,

00:48:43.380 --> 00:48:46.620
they have enough confidence
as being citizens

00:48:46.620 --> 00:48:51.810
of those countries to manifest
their religious difference,

00:48:51.810 --> 00:48:56.140
markers of their
identity, publicly.

00:48:56.140 --> 00:48:58.330
And this is an [INAUDIBLE] term.

00:48:58.330 --> 00:49:03.910
Citizenship is your capacity,
also not having ID cards,

00:49:03.910 --> 00:49:07.630
but also having the
courage in everyday life

00:49:07.630 --> 00:49:10.780
to show your
difference, not being

00:49:10.780 --> 00:49:15.070
scared, of keeping it at home.

00:49:15.070 --> 00:49:18.040
So this public life,
that's why this publicness

00:49:18.040 --> 00:49:21.970
is very important,
publicly visible.

00:49:21.970 --> 00:49:25.390
I'm not speaking of
Muslim minorities

00:49:25.390 --> 00:49:27.760
as visible minorities,
like category

00:49:27.760 --> 00:49:31.180
of race, although they are
also visible minorities,

00:49:31.180 --> 00:49:34.360
but they are actively
visible minorities.

00:49:34.360 --> 00:49:35.750
They are active minorities.

00:49:35.750 --> 00:49:38.740
This is Serge Moscovici,
a social psychologist

00:49:38.740 --> 00:49:41.530
in the '80s, who have
coined this term for women

00:49:41.530 --> 00:49:44.740
feminist movement,
how women became

00:49:44.740 --> 00:49:48.430
actively active minorities,
that is, they are transforming

00:49:48.430 --> 00:49:52.390
their conditions of life,
their subjectivities,

00:49:52.390 --> 00:49:54.970
actively into a
group of minorities.

00:49:54.970 --> 00:49:59.470
It's not only a way of
living it as a number,

00:49:59.470 --> 00:50:03.700
but it is a kind of active
appropriation of the situation

00:50:03.700 --> 00:50:10.090
which is neither in conformity
with Islamic patriarchal norms,

00:50:10.090 --> 00:50:14.530
nor in conformity with
feminist secular norms.

00:50:14.530 --> 00:50:16.490
That becomes a problem.

00:50:16.490 --> 00:50:22.450
So this assertive religious
difference, I would say,

00:50:22.450 --> 00:50:25.830
makes Muslims to be
more publicly visible.

00:50:25.830 --> 00:50:28.630
This assertiveness,
that's not being discreet,

00:50:28.630 --> 00:50:33.310
is perceived sometimes as
being aggressive, political,

00:50:33.310 --> 00:50:37.970
ideological, and not
just an issue of faith.

00:50:37.970 --> 00:50:43.900
So we can ask first
the question, when

00:50:43.900 --> 00:50:46.380
a religious symbol
becomes visible,

00:50:46.380 --> 00:50:48.600
visibility is a
relation of power.

00:50:48.600 --> 00:50:52.470
When it becomes visible to
us, it becomes visible when

00:50:52.470 --> 00:50:55.470
we ask questions, when
it is foreign to us,

00:50:55.470 --> 00:51:00.170
when we think it's alien,
we are not familiar with.

00:51:00.170 --> 00:51:02.720
There is a spatial
transgression.

00:51:02.720 --> 00:51:05.030
Boundaries are transgressed.

00:51:05.030 --> 00:51:08.370
When it is working
class covering,

00:51:08.370 --> 00:51:13.910
it wasn't a debate, neither
in France nor in Germany.

00:51:13.910 --> 00:51:18.895
Nobody has seen or noticed
the working class head

00:51:18.895 --> 00:51:21.440
scarf the head scarf of
working class people,

00:51:21.440 --> 00:51:23.600
or the grandmothers.

00:51:23.600 --> 00:51:26.780
It becomes visible when
it is the young students

00:51:26.780 --> 00:51:29.810
in high schools who are
covering themselves,

00:51:29.810 --> 00:51:33.960
or the teachers in German
schools, with the heads scarf.

00:51:33.960 --> 00:51:35.510
Then it becomes visible.

00:51:35.510 --> 00:51:38.720
So there is a transgression
of boundaries,

00:51:38.720 --> 00:51:43.620
but that transgression
is also indicating

00:51:43.620 --> 00:51:45.920
a social upward social mobility.

00:51:45.920 --> 00:51:48.100
They are succeeding
in public schools.

00:51:48.100 --> 00:51:53.250
They are succeeding in
their professional careers.

00:51:53.250 --> 00:51:57.150
But it becomes a problem
for the public perception.

00:51:57.150 --> 00:51:59.940
So there's subjectivity,
on the one hand,

00:51:59.940 --> 00:52:04.290
agency of these women, but
also public perception,

00:52:04.290 --> 00:52:05.640
on the other hand.

00:52:05.640 --> 00:52:09.910
So we need a
readjustment of that,

00:52:09.910 --> 00:52:13.060
and that readjustment is
not easy, because normally,

00:52:13.060 --> 00:52:19.500
in the European countries,
the secular belief,

00:52:19.500 --> 00:52:24.120
secularization, meant, in
spite of the differences

00:52:24.120 --> 00:52:25.180
among countries.

00:52:25.180 --> 00:52:27.420
We always speak of
French exceptionalism,

00:52:27.420 --> 00:52:30.900
but I don't think it's so
exceptional in these terms.

00:52:30.900 --> 00:52:34.055
We believe that religion
should be in the private.

00:52:34.055 --> 00:52:35.515
It should be regulated.

00:52:35.515 --> 00:52:36.390
It should be private.

00:52:36.390 --> 00:52:38.990
It as if something
very abstract.

00:52:38.990 --> 00:52:43.190
It's in your minds, or at
home, but religion is also

00:52:43.190 --> 00:52:45.570
something very public.

00:52:45.570 --> 00:52:48.090
And it is also embodied.

00:52:48.090 --> 00:52:52.030
It is related with
bodily practices.

00:52:52.030 --> 00:52:52.930
You cover yourself.

00:52:52.930 --> 00:52:54.980
It's something very personal.

00:52:54.980 --> 00:52:56.420
It is corporeal.

00:52:56.420 --> 00:52:58.330
It's same with dietary habits.

00:52:58.330 --> 00:53:00.580
It's same with praying.

00:53:00.580 --> 00:53:03.995
Saba Mahmood, who we
lost very recently,

00:53:03.995 --> 00:53:09.670
a very well known
anthropologist on Islam,

00:53:09.670 --> 00:53:13.060
she has shown how
much religious rituals

00:53:13.060 --> 00:53:17.350
is important to understand
as the embodiment of faith.

00:53:17.350 --> 00:53:20.790
Faith is not something
a belief, but it's also

00:53:20.790 --> 00:53:21.870
embodied practice.

00:53:21.870 --> 00:53:23.550
You survey.

00:53:23.550 --> 00:53:25.480
You control your faith.

00:53:25.480 --> 00:53:30.890
It's not something you have
it once for all on your paper.

00:53:30.890 --> 00:53:34.360
So these embodied practices,
like dietary habits,

00:53:34.360 --> 00:53:38.800
praying, covering, bring
forth all the controversies

00:53:38.800 --> 00:53:41.870
in European societies.

00:53:41.870 --> 00:53:45.070
And as I said, this
requires a readjustment

00:53:45.070 --> 00:53:48.070
between Muslim
subjectivities, what

00:53:48.070 --> 00:53:50.930
they think about
their own faith,

00:53:50.930 --> 00:53:53.710
and how the public
perceives them.

00:53:53.710 --> 00:53:56.200
You can say, in a
simple way, well,

00:53:56.200 --> 00:53:58.480
this would mean recognition.

00:53:58.480 --> 00:54:01.450
We need to recognize
the difference,

00:54:01.450 --> 00:54:07.100
religious difference, religious
practices, of another religion.

00:54:07.100 --> 00:54:14.460
But this creates a
destructive effect

00:54:14.460 --> 00:54:18.120
in the established norms
of a given society, that

00:54:18.120 --> 00:54:21.480
is, Muslim presence
is not something only

00:54:21.480 --> 00:54:24.720
to be recognized,
but also requires

00:54:24.720 --> 00:54:27.100
a two-way transformation.

00:54:27.100 --> 00:54:31.060
Somebody has asked, for the
first panel, have mentioned,

00:54:31.060 --> 00:54:35.300
we cannot take norms as
given, but norms are changing.

00:54:35.300 --> 00:54:38.890
So the fact that Muslim women
are covering themselves,

00:54:38.890 --> 00:54:44.440
and yet following emancipatory
trajectories of life,

00:54:44.440 --> 00:54:50.360
in terms of education,
going out of the house,

00:54:50.360 --> 00:54:54.160
nevertheless, questions
the secular feminist way

00:54:54.160 --> 00:54:57.200
of emancipation.

00:54:57.200 --> 00:55:00.950
So if we think in
that terms, so it's

00:55:00.950 --> 00:55:05.150
not only passive recognition,
but two-way change, which

00:55:05.150 --> 00:55:08.960
makes it very difficult. So
the recognition of these women

00:55:08.960 --> 00:55:09.630
failed.

00:55:09.630 --> 00:55:11.740
I go fast.

00:55:11.740 --> 00:55:16.850
Recognition of Muslim
women's covering,

00:55:16.850 --> 00:55:20.330
I would say, failed, because
now we have everywhere laws

00:55:20.330 --> 00:55:22.700
and things, and
especially it failed

00:55:22.700 --> 00:55:29.120
not only by state politics,
but also by spokespersons

00:55:29.120 --> 00:55:38.430
of one kind of feminism, who
denied agency of Muslim women.

00:55:38.430 --> 00:55:42.660
They didn't recognize
the agency that is

00:55:42.660 --> 00:55:44.720
embedded in covering yourself.

00:55:47.280 --> 00:55:53.370
So now, after 20 years
of debate on head scarf,

00:55:53.370 --> 00:55:55.720
still the name is problematic.

00:55:55.720 --> 00:56:00.180
When we don't know how to relate
ourselves with a difference,

00:56:00.180 --> 00:56:01.920
we try to invent names.

00:56:01.920 --> 00:56:03.810
We go back to the sources.

00:56:03.810 --> 00:56:09.630
Burka, hijab, as if Arabic
origins or other origins

00:56:09.630 --> 00:56:10.680
would give us the key.

00:56:10.680 --> 00:56:13.940
Or it's nearby,
which is in Europe.

00:56:13.940 --> 00:56:17.400
Burkini, in that matter,
is a very good example.

00:56:17.400 --> 00:56:22.710
I love burkini, because burkini
is something now you cannot go

00:56:22.710 --> 00:56:24.070
back to Arab origins.

00:56:26.610 --> 00:56:31.710
It is a beach culture,
and it's an accommodation,

00:56:31.710 --> 00:56:35.490
quite creative by a
form, and still maybe

00:56:35.490 --> 00:56:37.050
some of you have seen it.

00:56:37.050 --> 00:56:39.390
Last summer there
was a big scandal

00:56:39.390 --> 00:56:44.370
over burkini, and how
a woman with a burkini

00:56:44.370 --> 00:56:46.080
can go to a beach.

00:56:46.080 --> 00:56:51.000
So beach, do they belong to a
beach, Muslim woman, or beach

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:53.280
belongs to a Muslim woman?

00:56:53.280 --> 00:56:58.680
Now we don't have the guardians,
but we have policemen.

00:56:58.680 --> 00:57:00.240
So this is the
question I'm asking.

00:57:00.240 --> 00:57:04.670
Do we have to share the
same norms to belong?

00:57:04.670 --> 00:57:07.310
Is the condition of
citizenship means

00:57:07.310 --> 00:57:11.380
conformity with
established norms?

00:57:11.380 --> 00:57:15.670
And today, the
secularity or secularism

00:57:15.670 --> 00:57:20.480
plays the role of
redefining these norms,

00:57:20.480 --> 00:57:23.800
including feminist sexual
minorities becoming

00:57:23.800 --> 00:57:28.600
like a norm, as compulsory,
as something that people

00:57:28.600 --> 00:57:33.250
has to pass a test in
order to be citizen,

00:57:33.250 --> 00:57:37.420
not only within the
country, but also before--

00:57:37.420 --> 00:57:38.710
I think it was in Netherlands.

00:57:38.710 --> 00:57:41.390
You will help me in
the next, maybe, panel.

00:57:41.390 --> 00:57:47.980
There was a film showing some
kind of manners in sexual ways,

00:57:47.980 --> 00:57:51.340
quite free, to see
if the people who

00:57:51.340 --> 00:57:55.870
are asking to come to be migrant
can accept, can be tolerant,

00:57:55.870 --> 00:57:57.470
with these values.

00:57:57.470 --> 00:58:00.730
So our democracies are becoming
very sexual democracies

00:58:00.730 --> 00:58:02.470
in a way.

00:58:02.470 --> 00:58:10.360
And so the question of if
you are in conformity or not

00:58:10.360 --> 00:58:14.070
with the norms are becoming
a very important element

00:58:14.070 --> 00:58:18.240
of the political culture, public
culture, of European countries,

00:58:18.240 --> 00:58:21.960
in the last 20 years, with
the ways in which they have

00:58:21.960 --> 00:58:23.730
framed the question of Islam.

00:58:23.730 --> 00:58:27.730
It became a question of
norm, hierarchy of norms.

00:58:27.730 --> 00:58:29.730
I can say it in different ways.

00:58:29.730 --> 00:58:32.070
I can, say the way
we have thought

00:58:32.070 --> 00:58:34.620
in the western
countries of difference

00:58:34.620 --> 00:58:38.130
is either in terms
of religious minority

00:58:38.130 --> 00:58:42.420
rights, basically more
right-wing people,

00:58:42.420 --> 00:58:44.650
or multiculturalism.

00:58:44.650 --> 00:58:48.150
So two ways of thinking,
two frames of thinking,

00:58:48.150 --> 00:58:52.530
both multiculturalism
and religious rights,

00:58:52.530 --> 00:58:56.140
religious minority rights,
do not apply today.

00:58:56.140 --> 00:58:58.170
So they fall short.

00:58:58.170 --> 00:58:59.580
They have been criticized.

